%%TITLE
Association between age and high-risk human papilloma virus in Mexican oral cancer patients.
%%ABSTRACT
Studies reporting low prevalence of HPV in OSCC with declining age at presentation are increasing. The aim of this study was to determine the prevalence of HPV in a group of OSCC cases and controls in a Mexican population.The matched case-control study included 80 OSCC cases and 320 controls. HPV/DNA presence was evaluated through PCR amplification using three sets of consensus primers for the L1 gene. A conditional logistic regression analysis was carried out for the matched OSCC cases and controls. Interactions between risk factors and OCSS were tested in the construction process of the models.HPV prevalence was 5% in OSCC cases and 2.5% in controls. HPV-detected types were 16, 18 and 56. According to conditional logistics regression model, an association was detected between HR-HPV and OSCC. All HR-HPV-positive OSCC cases corresponded to young patients (<45Â years), non-smokers and non-alcohol drinkers.The HR-HPV can be a contributing factor to oral carcinogenesis, especially in younger individuals without known risk factors such as tobacco and alcohol.
%%MATERIAL AND METHODS
Study design
This case-control study was conducted from December 2007 to September 2011 at the Instituto Nacional de Cancerología (INCan), the Hospital General Dr. Manuel Gea Gonz'alez (DMGG) and the Clínica Estomatol'ogica Rafael Lozano of the Universidad Aut'onoma Metropoli- tana Xochimilco (UAM) at Mexico City. This study was
approved by the ethics committee of each participating institution. Details of the study were explained to all
participants and their written informed consent was obtained. The inclusion and exclusion criteria were per- formed according to the previous study (Gonzalez-Ra- mirez et al, 2011a).
Study population
Eighty patients with newly diagnosed, histologically con- ﬁrmed OSCC were enrolled. Three hundred and twenty controls (matched by gender and age [ 5 years]) were selected from two sources: the Ophthalmology Service of DMGG and the dental clinic of the UAM.
Data and sample collection
A questionnaire with demographic information, history of alcohol and tobacco consumption and family history of cancer was applied in all cases and controls. Current and former tobacco and alcohol categories were grouped in one category. Family history of cancer included ﬁrst- and second-line relatives. OSCC was deﬁned according to the International Classiﬁcation of Diseases and comprised malignancies of the tongue, gingival, ﬂoor of the mouth, hard palate, buccal mucosa and retromolar area (ICD-10 rubrics C01–C06) (WHO, 1992).
An incisional biopsy was taken from all OSCC cases and divided into two sections, one for conventional histo- pathology study and another for DNA assays. Tumour stage was assigned based on the best available staging

clinical or pathologic data using the American Joint Com- mittee on Cancer (AJCC) staging criteria (AJCC, 1997). In addition, cytological brushing for DNA collection was performed in patients and controls according to the previ- ous study (Gonzalez-Ramirez et al, 2011a).
DNA extraction
DNA was puriﬁed using the Wizard Genomic DNA Puriﬁ- cation kit (Promega, Madison, WI, USA) according to the manufacturer’s instructions and quantiﬁed by spectropho- tometry. DNA puriﬁcation and HPV-detection assays were performed in separate laboratories to minimize the possi- bility of contamination.
HPV determination
The presence and quality of human genomic DNA was veriﬁed in all samples by ampliﬁcation of b-globin gene (Saiki et al, 1985).
To ensure an optimal detection of HPV genomic sequences, DNA samples were submitted to PCR ampli- ﬁcation with three sets of consensus primers recognizing distinct size fragments of L1 gene (Carrillo et al, 2004): MY09/MY11 (Bauer et al, 1991), GP5+/GP6+ (Jacobs et al, 1995) and L1C1/L1C2.1/L1C2.2 (Husnjak et al, 2000). Additionally, speciﬁc oligonucleotides for HPV-
16 and HPV-18 E6 gene were used (Sugiyama et al, 2003). DNA from a CaSki cervical cancer cell line (HPV-16 positive) and DNA from an HPV-positive cervical cancer specimen were used as positive controls. A reagent mix containing all the PCR reagents without DNA was included as negative control in all PCR runs. PCR products were subjected to 2% agarose gel electro- phoresis. DNA bands were stained with ethidium bro- mide and photographed under UV transillumination. One HPV PCR product, whose sample resulted negative for HPV-16 or HPV-18 ampliﬁcation, was puriﬁed and sub- sequently sequenced in an automatic sequencer 3100 Avant (Applied Biosystems, Foster City, CA, USA) using the Big Dye Terminator v3.1 Cycle Sequencing Kit (Applied Biosystems). The obtained sequence was compared with the GenBank database (National Center for Biotechnology Information) by using the BLAST program (Altschul et al, 1997).
Statistical analysis
Statistical analysis was performed using SPSS 11.5 and STATA (StataCorp Relase:10, TX, USA) software. Demographic data of patients and controls were described as frequencies and means for categorical and continuous variables, respectively. Conditional logistic regression analysis was carried out for the matched OSCC cases and controls. Odds ratios (ORs) and 95% conﬁdence intervals (CI) were constructed. Interactions between risk factors and OCSS were tested in the construction process of the models. P-value for statistical signiﬁcance was set at P < 0.05.
